Abstract

Federated learning (FL) is a new machine learning paradigm to overcome the challenge of data silos and has garnered significant attention. However, through our observations, a globally effective trained model may performance disparities in different clients. This implies that the jointly trained models by clients may lead to unfair outcomes. On the other hand, relevant studies indicate that the transmission of gradients or models in federated learning can also give rise to privacy leakage issues, such as membership inference attacks.

To address the first issue mentioned above, we propose a federated algorithm with fairness, termed FedFair. Building upon FedFair, we introduce privacy protection to form the FedFDP algorithm to address the second issue mentioned above. In FedFDP, we devise a fairness-aware clipping strategy to achieve differential privacy while adjusting fairness. Additionally, for the extra uploaded loss values, we present an adaptive clipping approach to maximize utility. Furthermore, we theoretically prove that our algorithm converges and ensures differential privacy. Lastly, Extensive experimental results demonstrate that FedFair and FedFDP significantly outperforms state-of-the-art solutions in terms of model performance and fairness. The code is accessible at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/FedFDP-E754.

1 Introduction

Federated Learning (FL) McMahan et al. (2017) is a distributed machine learning framework that allows clients to collaboratively train a shared model without revealing their individual datasets. After training their local models, each client transmits only the model parameters, not the raw training data, to a central server. The server aggregates these parameters to update the global model, which is then sent back to clients for further training. Because its ability to overcome data silos by jointly improving model performance without the need to upload local data, FL has gained significant attention in recent yearÂ Zhu et al. (2021)Lee et al. (2022). In particular, many studies have made great breakthroughs in model performanceÂ Wang et al. (2020); Li et al. (2020a, 2021b) and communication costsÂ Wang et al. (2019); Ling et al. (2023) in FL.

However, recent research indicates that trained parameters can leak data privacy, such as the recovery of original data Zhu et al. (2019) or the membership inference attack Song et al. (2017). Moreover, Melis et al. Melis et al. (2022) demonstrated that clientsâ€™ training data can be leaked through shared models. In order to enhance data privacy in the FL, numerous scholars have begun integrating techniques such as differential privacy (DP)Â Dwork et al. (2014), homomorphic encryption Paillier (1999), and secure multi-party computation Yao (1982) into the federated learning framework. Among these, DP has emerged as the most widely acknowledged approach for privacy protection in federated learning, owing to its minimal computational overhead and rigorous mathematical framework. Many works Abadi et al. (2016); Carlini et al. (2019); Feldman (2020) have demonstrated that by adding proper DP noise in the training phase, the resulted machine learning models can prevent unintentional leakage of private training data, such as membership inference attacks.

Another easily overlooked critical issue in federated learning is fairness. The globally trained model collaboratively by clients may exhibit significant performance disparities across datasets held by different clients. As shown in Fig.1, where the red dots indicate the test accuracy of the global model across various clients after the completion of federated learning using the FedAvg McMahan et al. (2017) algorithm. And we can see the globally trained model applied to individual clients, the performance significant performance disparities across differential clients. More and more scholars have begun to notice this unfair phenomenon and initiated research on itÂ  Wang et al. (2020); Li et al. (2020b).

While numerous articles separately discuss fairness and differential privacy protection in federated learning, there is a lack of research integrating both aspects into federated learning. Balancing model performance, fairness, and differential privacy protection in federated learning presents a challenging problem. This paper aims to investigate fairness and differential privacy protection mechanisms in federated learning. By analyzing the relationship between them, we propose a federated learning framework that ensures both fairness and differential privacy protection, effectively guaranteeing model performance.

Our main contributions are listed below:

  1. 1.

    Firstly, we propose a fairness-aware federated algorithm, denoted as algorithm FedFair by designing a new local loss function that is constructed to simultaneously optimize the two objectives of fairness and model performance (SectionÂ 4). FedFair algorithm achieves the excellent fairness, as shown by the green dots in Fig.1.

  2. 2.

    Building upon FedFair, we propose algorithm FedFDP to achieve differential privacy protection (SectionÂ 5) . Particularly, we device a fairness-aware gradient clipping strategy to ensures both differential privacy and allows for the adjustment of fairness in federated learning (SectionÂ 5.1). Additionally, we propose an adaptive clipping approach method for the additional loss values uploaded by each client to achieve optimal utility (SectionÂ 5.2).

  3. 3.

    Furthermore, we demonstrate there exist an optimal fairness parameter Î»ğœ†\lambda value to balance the model performance and fairness through the convergence analysis (SectionÂ 6).

  4. 4.

    And then, we perform privacy loss analysis of our algorithm FedFDP by the notion of RÃ©nyi differential privacy (RDP) to prove that it satisfies the differential privacy (SectionÂ 7).

  5. 5.

    Lastly, through a comprehensive empirical evaluation on three public datasets, we confirm that FedFair and FedFDP outperforms the state-of-the-art solutions in terms of model performance and fairness (SectionÂ 8).

2 Related Work

2.1 Fairness in Federated Learning

In the field of machine learning, a multitude of fairness concepts have been advanced (Mehrabi et al. Mehrabi et al. (2021), Yuxin et al. Shi et al. (2021)), each highlighting specific facets and addressing the concerns of diverse stakeholder groups. For instance, Mohri et al. Mohri et al. (2019) advocate for Good-Intent Fairness, while Zhou et al. Zhou et al. (2021) embrace Selection Fairness. Cong and Lyu et al. Cong et al. (2020)Lyu et al. (2020) employ principles from game theory Rabin (1993) to steer the allocation of rewards.

Currently, the predominant fairness criterion in Federated Learning is â€œPerformance Parityâ€, as proposed by Li et al. Li et al. (2020b). This criterion aims to ensure fairness by evaluating the consistency of performance across different client devices in federated learning. This definition is widely adopted. Zhao et al. Zhao and Joshi (2022) suggested replacing the loss amplification mechanism in Li et al. (2020b) with a straightforward weight reallocation mechanism. Li et al. Li et al. (2021b) focus on optimizing the fairness of local models in personalized federated learning.

2.2 Federated Learning with Differential Privacy

Federated learning with differential privacy has become a common privacy protection method in federated learning. Enayat et al. Ullah et al. (2023) dynamically adjust the compression rate to minimize communication rounds in federated learning by responding to changes in training loss. Zhou et al. Zhou et al. (2023) investigated the effects of local iterations when utilizing the Laplace mechanism for perturbation. Fu et al. Fu et al. (2022) introduced adaptive noise adding, customizing it for different clients and communication rounds based on observed fluctuations in loss values. Ling et al. Ling et al. (2023) determined the optimal number of local epochs through convergence analysis, striking a balance between communication resources and privacy budget. Raouf et al. Kerkouche et al. (2021) improved model accuracy by updating only a fixed subset of model weights while keeping others unchanged.

The aforementioned works each independently address either fairness or privacy protection in federated learning. To the best of our knowledge, we are the first to concurrently consider both fairness and privacy in the context of federated learning.

5 Proposed Algorithm: FedFDP

In this section, we propose the FedFDP by integrating differential privacy protection base on FedFair. The flow of FedFDP algorithm as shown in Fig. 2. 8 Experiments

In this section, we conduct experiments to demonstrate the performance and fairness of FedFair and FedFDP using three real datasets. Additionally, we investigate the impact of various factors on FedFDP, such as fairness hyperparameter Î»ğœ†\lambda, original clipping bound Cğ¶C, heterogeneity and scalability. The impact of heterogeneity and scalability please refer to Appendix A.3).

8.1 Default Settings

We conducted experiments on three computer vision (CV) datasets: MNIST LeCun et al. (1998), FashionMNIST Xiao et al. (2017), and CIFAR10 Krizhevsky (2009). And we comparised our algorithms to six baselines, which include FedAvgMcMahan et al. (2017), SCAFFLODKarimireddy et al. (2020), FedProxLi et al. (2020a), FedDynAcar et al. (2021), ALI-DPFLLing et al. (2023) and q-FFLLi et al. (2020b). For the details of parameters settings and the descriptions of baselines please refer to AppendixÂ A.3.1.

8.2 Results

Performance and Fairness. The experimental results of the FedFair algorithm and baseline methods are shown in Table 1. FedFair notably enhances fairness while maintaining substantial model performance across the MNIST, FashionMNIST, and CIFAR10 datasets, with respective increases of 17.0%, 25.7%, and 9.5%. And Table 2 shows the experimental results of the FedFDP algorithm and baseline methods. Under the same privacy budget, FedFDP demonstrates improvements in model accuracy of 1.2%, 1.8%, and 0.4% compared to the best baseline on the three datasets, while also enhancing fairness by 30.3%, 6.7%, and 27.8% respectively compared to the best baseline.

Impact of different Î»ğœ†\lambda. We investigated the correlation between Î»ğœ†\lambda and fairness Î¨Î¨\Psi in FedFDF algorithm. As depicted in Figure 4, our findings align with the theoretical analysis in Section 6.1: an initial increase in Î»ğœ†\lambda leads to a decrease in Î¨Î¨\Psi, followed by an increase.

Impact of different Cğ¶C. In Section 5.1, we emphasized that excessively large or small values of Cğ¶C cannot ensure both performance and fairness simultaneously. As illustrated in Figure 5, we examined the correlation between Cğ¶C, performance, and fairness across two datasets, with Cğ¶C taking values of [0.01, 0.1, 1, 5, 10]. Although Î¨Î¨\Psi reaches its minimum when C=1ğ¶1C=1, at this point, due to excessive noise addition, the model does not converge. As Cğ¶C continues to increase, the modelâ€™s performance further deteriorates, resulting in an increase in Î¨Î¨\Psi. When C=0.1ğ¶0.1C=0.1, both accuracy and Î¨Î¨\Psi achieve relatively good values.

9 Conclusion

In this paper, firstly, we propose a FedFair algorithm effectively addresses fairness concerns by optimizing a novel local loss function. Building upon FedFair, we propose the FedFDP, incorporates a fairness-aware gradient clipping strategy and an adaptive clipping method for additional loss values to achieve both fairness and differential privacy protection. And then, through convergence analysis, we determine the existence of an optimal fairness parameter, Î»ğœ†\lambda, striking a balance between model performance and fairness. We conduct a comprehensive privacy analysis of our approach using RDP and validate our algorithms through extensive experiments. The results indicate that FedFair and FedFDP significantly outperforms state-of-the-art solutions in terms of model performance and fairness. We believe our work contributes a valuable FL framework for addressing fairness and privacy challenges.

A.3.2 Baselines introduction

The baseline methods included in the comparison are:

  • â€¢

    FedAvgMcMahan et al. [2017]: FedAvg is the most classic algorithm in federated learning. In fact, we can set Î»ğœ†\lambda to 0, transforming FedFDP into the FedAvg algorithm.

  • â€¢

    SCAFFLODKarimireddy et al. [2020]: SCAFFOLD uses control variates (variance reduction) to correct for the â€™client-driftâ€™ in its local updates. It requires significantly fewer communication rounds and is not affected by data heterogeneity or client sampling.

  • â€¢

    FedProxLi et al. [2020a]: FedProx introduces a proximal term to the objective function to address the issues of systems heterogeneity and statistical heterogeneity in federated learning.

  • â€¢

    FedDynAcar et al. [2021]: FedDyn adds linear and quadratic penalty terms to the objective function to solve the problem of inconsistency between the minima of the local-device level empirical loss and those of the global empirical loss.

  • â€¢

    ALI-DPFLLing et al. [2023]: ALI-DPFL dynamically obtains the optimal number of epochs for each round of communication by minimizing the convergence upper bound, thereby addressing the imbalance between local privacy budgets and communication resources.

  • â€¢

    q-FFLLi et al. [2020b]: q-FFL amplifies the loss values of clients, equivalent to giving larger update weights to poorly performing clients, in order to cater to the underperforming clients, uniforming model performance across multiple devices.

A.3.3 Herterogeneity and Scalability

As shown in Table 4 and 5, we conducted additional experiments on the MNIST, FashionMNIST, and CIFAR10 datasets to compare the performance of FedFDP with that of six other algorithms in terms of Heterogeneity and Scalability. The Heterogeneity experiments were mainly conducted in three heterogeneous scenarios, extending from the default Dâ€‹iâ€‹râ€‹(0.1)ğ·ğ‘–ğ‘Ÿ0.1Dir(0.1) to include Dâ€‹iâ€‹râ€‹(0.5)ğ·ğ‘–ğ‘Ÿ0.5Dir(0.5) and Dâ€‹iâ€‹râ€‹(1)ğ·ğ‘–ğ‘Ÿ1Dir(1). Scalability was expanded from the default 10 clients to include 20 and 50 clients.

Heterogeneities. Tables 4 and 5 show that when confronted with diverse data distributions exhibiting varying levels of heterogeneity, both FedFair and FedFDP outperform baseline methods in accuracy while maintaining significant fairness. With the exception of the Dâ€‹iâ€‹râ€‹(0.5)ğ·ğ‘–ğ‘Ÿ0.5Dir(0.5) scenario, where they fall slightly short of q-FFL, they respectively demonstrated fairness improvements of 17.0% and 50% for FedFair and 30.3% and 18.9% for FedFDP compared to the best baselines in Dâ€‹iâ€‹râ€‹(0.1)ğ·ğ‘–ğ‘Ÿ0.1Dir(0.1) and Dâ€‹iâ€‹râ€‹(1.0)ğ·ğ‘–ğ‘Ÿ1.0Dir(1.0).

Scalability. Table 4 demonstrates that, with accuracy mostly superior to baselines, FedFair exhibited fairness improvements of 9.5%, 15.4%, and 0.01% across three client counts. Table 5 indicates that as the number of clients increases, FedFDP outperformed the best baselines by 0.36%, 0.18%, and 0.59% in accuracy, except in the 50 clients scenario, where it demonstrated fairness improvements of 27.8% and 24.1%.
